'''Callum William McCowatt''' (born 30 April 1999) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Winger (association football)|left winger]] for [[Danish Superliga]] club [[Silkeborg IF|Silkeborg]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

==Club career==
Following his graduation from [[Westlake Boys High School]], McCowatt joined the [[Olé Football Academy]] in early 2015, playing league football for Olé-affiliated club [[Western Suburbs FC (New Zealand)|Western Suburbs]]. During his time with the academy, McCowatt was named in the youth squad of [[Team Wellington]] for the 2016 [[National Youth League (New Zealand)|National Youth League]] season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Team Wellington Youth Squad named for 2016 Campaign |url=http://www.twfc.co.nz/news-2/2016/9/19/team-wellington-youth-squad-named-for-2016-campaign |website=[[Team Wellington]] |accessdate=19 September 2016 |archive-date=26 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926152351/http://www.twfc.co.nz/news-2/2016/9/19/team-wellington-youth-squad-named-for-2016-campaign |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Auckland City===
Following his time at Western Suburbs, McCowatt moved to [[New Zealand Football Championship|ISPS Handa Premiership]] club [[Auckland City FC|Auckland City]] along with fellow Olé graduates [[Dalton Wilkins]] and Owen Parker-Price on 26 September 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Navy Blues sign Ole Academy trio |url=http://www.aucklandcityfc.com/news/433/12/Navy-Blues-sign-Ole-Academy-trio/ |website=[[Auckland City FC]] |accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref> Though he was originally intended for the youth team{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}, McCowatt eventually started every game Auckland City played that season, including the [[2017 FIFA Club World Cup|FIFA Club World Cup]] and [[2017 OFC Champions League|OFC Champions League]] campaigns. McCowatt scored the only goal in the [[2017–18 New Zealand Football Championship#Grand final|grand final]] as Auckland City defeated Team Wellington 1–0 to lift the league title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=When Auckland City needed a winner, Callum McCowatt found a way |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/102746498/when-auckland-city-needed-a-winner-callum-mccowatt-found-a-way |accessdate=14 October 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=1 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Late Callum McCowatt goal gives Auckland City a record seventh national title |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/102746434/late-callum-mccowatt-winner-gives-auckland-city-a-record-seventh-national-title |accessdate=14 October 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=1 April 2018}}</ref>

Following McCowatt's success in his debut season, in which he formed an attacking trio with [[Ryan de Vries]] and [[Emiliano Tade]], he earned a trial with [[Eredivisie]] club [[Sparta Rotterdam]], but was not offered a contract.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/106115619/young-kiwi-footballers-callum-mccowatt-and-eli-just-set-for-spells-at-european-clubs|title=Young Kiwi footballers Callum McCowatt and Eli Just set for spells at European clubs|website=Stuff|date=8 August 2018 |language=en|access-date=10 July 2019}}</ref>

===Eastern Suburbs===
On 21 November 2018, McCowatt continued his relationship with the Olé academy, signing with affiliated club [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]]. He scored 21 goals in 16 appearances in the [[2018–19 New Zealand Football Championship|2018–19 season]],<ref name="opener" /> including a hat-trick in the [[2018–19 New Zealand Football Championship#Grand final|grand final]] against [[Team Wellington]] which his team won 3–0. He was awarded the [[Steve Sumner Trophy]] for player of the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/domestic/111676313/callum-mccowatt-stars-as-eastern-suburbs-win-national-mens-football-league-final|title=Callum McCowatt stars as Eastern Suburbs win national men's football league final|website=Stuff|date=31 March 2019 |language=en|access-date=10 July 2019}}</ref>

===Wellington Phoenix===
On 26 June 2019, it was announced that McCowatt signed with the [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] who play in the [[A-League]] on a one-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/113781610/wellington-phoenix-confirm-the-signing-of-new-zealand-under20-forward-callum-mccowatt|title=Gun Kiwi goal-scorer Callum McCowatt steps up with Wellington Phoenix|website=Stuff|date=26 June 2019 |language=en|access-date=10 July 2019}}</ref> McCowatt scored his first goal for the Phoenix in their [[2019 FFA Cup|FFA Cup]] lost to the [[Brisbane Strikers FC|Brisbane Strikers]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix pay the penalty in shock FFA Cup defeat against Strikers |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/114811123/wellington-phoenix-knocked-out-of-ffa-cup-on-penalties |accessdate=15 October 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=8 August 2019}}</ref> before he made his professional debut in a 0–1 loss to [[Western United FC|Western United]] in the Phoenix [[2019–20 Wellington Phoenix FC season|season opener]].<ref name="opener">{{cite news |title=Wellington Phoenix youngster Callum McCowatt sure the goals will come |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/116573107/wellington-phoenix-youngster-callum-mccowatt-sure-the-goals-will-come |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=15 October 2019}}</ref>

===Helsingør===
On 6 September 2020, McCowatt signed a contract with [[FC Helsingør|Helsingør]] who play in the [[Danish 1st Division]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fchelsingor.dk/2020/09/06/fc-helsingoer-henter-new-zealandsk-angriber/|title=FC HELSINGØR PICKS UP NEW ZEALAND STRIKER|website=FC Helsingør|date=6 September 2020 |language=da|access-date=11 April 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/94978|title=Callum McCowatt goes Danish|website=NZ Football|language=en|access-date=11 April 2021}}</ref> On 18 October 2020, McCowatt made his debut for FC Helsingør, when he was substituted on in the 70th minute.<ref name=intMcCowatt>{{cite web |title=C. McCowatt |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/callum-mccowatt/425376/ |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=29 March 2021}}</ref> McCowatt scored his first goal for the club against [[HB Køge]] in the [[2020–21 Danish 1st Division#Promotion Group|Danish 1st Division]] promotion group match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.1-division.dk/kamp/2020-2021/april/fc-helsingor-hb-koge|title=fc helsingor-hb koge|website=1st Division|date=25 March 2021|language=da|access-date=11 April 2021|archive-date=11 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210411121044/https://www.1-division.dk/kamp/2020-2021/april/fc-helsingor-hb-koge|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Silkeborg===
After three seasons at Helsingør, [[Danish Superliga]] club [[Silkeborg IF|Silkeborg]] confirmed on 4 July 2023, that McCowatt had joined the club on a deal until the end of 2027.<ref>{{cite web |title=Silkeborg IF har købt den newzealandske landsholdsspiller Callum McCowatt i FC Helsingør. |trans-title=Silkeborg IF has bought the New Zealand national team player Callum McCowatt from FC Helsingør. |url=https://www.silkeborgif.com/sif-koeber-callum-mccowatt/ |website=Silkeborg IF |date=4 July 2023 |language=Danish |access-date=20 September 2023}}</ref> McCowatt made his Silkeborg debut on 23 July 2023 in the season opener against [[Brøndby IF|Brøndby]], being substituted on in the 82nd minute.<ref>{{cite web |title=Silkeborg IF 1-2 Brøndby |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/670877 |website=[[ESPN]] |access-date=20 September 2023}}</ref> On 4 August 2023, McCowatt scored his first goal for Silkeborg in a 2–1 league win over [[Vejle BK|Vejle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Callum McCowatt kom ind fra bænken og udlignede for SIF, inden Alexander Lind sikrede sejren på 2-1 over Vejle i overtiden. |trans-title=Callum McCowatt came on from the bench and equalized for SIF, before Alexander Lind secured the 2-1 victory over Vejle in extra time. |url=https://www.silkeborgif.com/en-droem-der-blev-til-virkelighed/ |website=Silkeborg IF |date=5 August 2023 |language=Danish |access-date=20 September 2023}}</ref>

On 21 September 2025, McCowatt scored his first [[hat-trick]] for Silkeborg in a 3–3 away draw against [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] in the Superliga.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.silkeborgif.com/mccowatt-hattrick-bag-comeback-og-point-i-parken/ |title=McCowatt-hattrick bag comeback og point i Parken |publisher=Silkeborg IF |language=Danish |date=21 September 2025 |access-date=21 September 2025}}</ref> On 9 December, he was named Silkeborg Player of the Year for 2025.<ref name="poty">{{cite web |url=https://www.silkeborgif.com/callum-mccowatt-er-aarets-spiller-i-sif-2025/ |title=Callum McCowatt er Årets Spiller i SIF 2025 |publisher=Silkeborg IF |language=Danish |date=9 December 2025 |access-date=12 December 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
McCowatt got his first international call-up for the [[New Zealand men's national under-17 football team|New Zealand U17 team]] for the [[2015 FIFA U-17 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Football: NZ U-17s named for World Cup |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11524754 |accessdate=15 October 2019 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=6 October 2015}}</ref> He played four matches, starting in one.<ref name="soccerway">{{cite web |title=C.McCowatt |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/-/425376/ |website=Soccerway |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref>
McCowatt was named in the [[New Zealand men's national under-20 football team|New Zealand U20 squad]] for the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/112868265/talented-new-zealand-team-heading-into-fifa-under20-world-cup-full-of-confidence|title=Talented New Zealand team heading into Fifa Under-20 World Cup full of confidence|website=Stuff|date=23 May 2019 |language=en|access-date=10 July 2019}}</ref> He was named in the starting lineup in 3 matches but failed to score.<ref name="soccerway"/>

McCowatt made his senior international debut on 15 November 2019, starting for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] in a friendly against [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]]. McCowatt opened the scoring, marking his first ever goal for the national team, before New Zealand went on to lose 1–3.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Callum McCowatt scores on debut as new-look All Whites lose to Republic of Ireland |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/117073735/callum-mccowatt-scores-on-debut-as-newlook-all-whites-lose-to-republic-of-ireland |accessdate=15 November 2019 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

On 25 June 2021, McCowatt was called up to the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|Tokyo 2020 Olympics]] with the [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand U23s]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Squads named for Tokyo 2020 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1223399&newsfeedPageNum=2 |accessdate=23 July 2021 |publisher=[[New Zealand Football]]}}</ref>
He made his [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] debut on 22 July 2021 in the OlyWhites' first ever Olympic win, a 1–0 victory against [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=OlyWhites make perfect start to Tokyo Olympics with famous win over South Korea |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/olympics/125835593/olywhites-make-perfect-start-to-tokyo-olympics-with-famous-win-over-south-korea |accessdate=23 July 2021 |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

